The issue integrating Ere-ZisK is because zisk requires large shared memory and locked memory, but `kurtosis` doesn't support that yet. We upgraded ZisK a bit but this requirement is still needed, the workaround is to set the default value of the `dockerd` by:

```json
{
  "default-shm-size": "32G",
  "default-ulimits": {
    "memlock": {
      "Name": "memlock",
      "Hard": -1,
      "Soft": -1
    }
  }
}
```

For other zkVMs, they don't have such requirements, but they are slower than ZisK so probably harder to test with (need to set slot time longer).

Previously I'm starting the whole `zkboost` stack by separate `docker-compose.yml`, to integrate with devnet spin up by `kurtosis`. There is one example in https://github.com/eth-act/zkboost/blob/master/docker/example/testnet/docker-compose.yml, which runs `zkboost` with 2 ZisK prover (proves Ethrex and Reth) with 4 GPUs (I'll need to update the `README` there to make the scripts work again)

Do you think the docker compose way is good enough? Or should we try again to integrate Ere into `ethereum-package` so we can test zkboost with real prover?
